<exercise checkit-seed="0048" checkit-slug="M1" checkit-title="Multiplying matrices">
  <statement>
    <p>Of the following three matrices, only two may be multiplied.
      <md><mrow>A= \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 &amp; 2 \\
0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -3
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; B= \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
2 &amp; 1 &amp; -5 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\
0 &amp; -2 &amp; -5 \\
-1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0
\end{array}\right]  &amp; &amp; C= \left[\begin{array}{cc}
-1 &amp; 1 \\
1 &amp; 5 \\
1 &amp; 6 \\
-2 &amp; -3
\end{array}\right] </mrow></md>
      Explain which two can be multiplied and why. Then show how to find their product.</p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <me>BA= \left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 &amp; 20 \\
0 &amp; -8 \\
0 &amp; 13 \\
-1 &amp; -4
\end{array}\right] </me>
  </answer>
</exercise>

